data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span conversion rules** cause `array.Contains(x)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>()`. Expression trees **cannot represent** span-based method calls, so this fails at runtime.

## How to fix it

Force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<T>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from selecting the span overload and keep the expression tree valid. The same issue affects `array.Reverse()` (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version) — use `Enumerable.Reverse(array)` there too.
